              <span id="reviewTextContainer3763379489" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13017617843546080438">In this, 4th book of the series, we get to engage with the Seymour brothers, Katherine Parr, Archbishop Cranmer, and the terrible Bishop Bonner. While I enjoyed this book, there was much theological discussion, which leads me to believe that Sansom may come from a worldview that is opposed to biblical Christianity, and that soured me a bit (being a biblically based Christian). The horrors that mankind visited upon each other during the Tudor era were so horrible, that the criticism didn’t need t</span>
  <span id="freeText13017617843546080438" style="display:none">In this, 4th book of the series, we get to engage with the Seymour brothers, Katherine Parr, Archbishop Cranmer, and the terrible Bishop Bonner. While I enjoyed this book, there was much theological discussion, which leads me to believe that Sansom may come from a worldview that is opposed to biblical Christianity, and that soured me a bit (being a biblically based Christian). The horrors that mankind visited upon each other during the Tudor era were so horrible, that the criticism didn’t need to fall so hard upon the Protestant view, in my opinion. It was all awful, the evil that was done in God’s name. I mean, let us not forget the inquisition. <br /><br />That all said, Shardlake continues to be an interesting and likable character, as are the other characters that people Sansom’s series. 4 full stars. </span>
